title: For Sale:  Caldwell LEAD SLED Recoil-Eliminating Shooting Rest NIB
location: N. Garland, Sachse, Rowlett, Dallas, Texas
postcontent:
FOR SALE
>>>> Caldwell LEAD SLED Recoil-Eliminating Shooting Rest <<<<
New in the box - never assembled. Model 820216

A LEAD SLED is a strong, steel device that holds a rifle, slug gun or other high-power gun in place as you shoot. This tool takes the recoil of the shot, protecting your shoulder and eliminating the instinct to flinch, which can ruin your aim. If you are a veteran shooter with a bad shoulder, or a beginning shooter learning to perfect your form, the lead sled can protect you from injury.
HOW TO USE
1. Place the lead sled on a platform that comes to the level you would like to shoot, or on the ground if you wish to take a shot lying on your stomach. The lead sled itself is only about a foot tall from the bottom tray to the gun holder.
2. Place your 25 pound bags of lead shot (or sand) in the tray at the bottom of the lead sled. These bags add weight and help the lead sled take the recoil of the shot.
3.Place the butt of the rifle in the back pad. Place the front of the gun in the front pad. This placement should be comfortable when you are holding the butt of the rifle with your dominant hand and holding it on the neck with your supporting hand.
4. Turn the dial in the middle of the lead sled to raise or lower the position of the gun. Once again, this should be at a comfortable height when in shooting position. Tighten the center lock when you have the gun in its correct position.
5. Load your gun, come to aim with the help of the lead sled and fire. Lead sleds take approximately 90 percent of the recoil. If you still feel significant recoil, you may not have placed the gun properly in the sled.

title: For Sale:  Remington 870 Police 12 Gauge, Heavy Duty
postcontent:
This shotgun is a police squad car gun with the hardened, heavy duty parts you don't find in the store bought version making it a real animal. Working the action, it feels much sturdier when compared to a new 870 with the same size barrel. It has a 20 inch barrel with rifle sights and an extension giving 7 in the tube and one in the chamber for 8 total shots. It is a Parkerized finish. 
 I purchased this gun for a home defense weapon and wanted my 104 pound wife to be able to handle it also so I put a new Black Hawk Sped Ops recoil reduction stock on it to shorten it and cut down on the recoil. While she can handle the recoil, it's still a bit too heavy for her to handle comfortably. 
It shot very well when I grouped it with Winchester Military OO buck. Opening quickly from 5 to 10 yards to about 6-10 inches, nice for close, quick, poor light conditions, but still kept all 9 in a silhouette target at 25 yards. With Federal Truball Vita-Shok slugs, I sighted it to hit the center of a 6 inch target at 25 yards (3 inches high). When I backed off to 100 and held 6 o'clock it hit exactly at 6 o'clock in the black. Can't expect more than that from open sights with a rifle. 
I put an MI Garand sling on it and it works nicely with the quick release sling swivels. I will also include the original wood furniture though there is a small crack in the pistol grip that I would pin if I were to use it. No problem with the pump grip. All the sighting in was done with the wood on, not the new Black Hawk stock.
If you would like more pictures or other info, just email me.

postcontent:

When St. Louis City PD switched from .38s to the 9mm Beretta, a group purchase was offered to the officers for a couple of different S&W 9mms for off duty use.  This 6946 is one of those weapons. title: For Sale:  CZ 455 Varmint
postcontent:
Up for sale is a CZ 455 Varmint. This is one of those rifles that you can tell it's an heirloom quality piece just by the way it feels. It has a solid Walnut stock with beautiful cut checkering. The barrel is 20.5" long and heavy profile. The action is super smooth. The trigger is extremely light. It is by far the most accurate 22LR that I've owned. That list includes Savage, Ruger, Marlin, and Browning rifles. 

This gun is perfect for bench shooting and varmint hunting. 

One thing to note about the 455 series is that if you want to switch barrels or calibers all you need to do is buy the barrel kit and swap it out. The receiver, stock, and bolt will work with 22lr, 22WMR, and 17HMR barrels. 

It comes with what you see. The rifle and the original 5 round CZ magazine. 

Other than a few small dings in the stock, it's in good shape. 

This gun is $420 on Bud's. That doesn't include the FFL transfer fee. I'm asking $350 OBO.
